node.text: Rep. Elise Stefanik went from moderate New York Republican to full-on Donald Trump loyalist — to the point where, now, she's replaced Rep. Liz Cheney in House GOP leadership. What changed? On this week's Battleground podcast, Faiz Shakir and Amanda Litman host writer Charlotte Alter, author of a new book about millennial leaders, to figure out the answer. Spoiler alert: It all comes back to Donald Trump, Donald Trump, Donald Trump.

node.title: Understanding the Evolution of Rep. Elise Stefanik

node.text:
According to The Center for Responsive Politics, the 2020 elections cost a combined $14.4 billion. That money has to come from somewhere, and while the last cycle saw an unprecedented number of small donors, a lot of those dollars came from billionaires.

Amanda and Faiz talk with Teddy Schleifer, a senior reporter covering money and influence (or billionaires) for Recode. They discuss how tech billionaires with relatively little political experience, like Reid Hoffman and Dustin Moskovitz, spent gobs of money trying to get Democrats get elected; whether it actually helped; and whether Democrats should partner with billionaires in the first place.

node.text: Mika Brzezinski was constantly wading her way through reporting jobs that didn't fit her, half-baked successes, anxiety, and, of course, misogyny. But she always knew there was something bigger waiting for her — she wouldn't have set a news report about Paris Hilton on fire on-air if she didn't. On Just Something About Her, Mika recounts the road that led to the creation of "Morning Joe."

node.text: Tram Nguyen played a huge role in flipping Virginia blue. She is the co-founder and Co-Executive Director of New Virginia Majority, an organization that has registered nearly 300,000 new voters and knocked on 3.1 million doors to get out the vote. They've also played a vital role in restoring formerly incarcerated Virginians' right to vote, expanding Medicaid, and getting undocumented immigrants the right to drivers' licenses. Amanda and Faiz speak with her to learn how she did it and to find out what advice she has for activists and politically engaged citizens, in purple and red states, with similar aspirations.

node.text: CNN Anchor Don Lemon knew from a young age: to be successful in his career, he had to remain in the closet. node.title: Don Lemon on Hell & High Water

node.text: In January 2020, longtime GOP pollster and strategist Frank Luntz had a stroke — one he's still struggling to recover from. And there's nothing like a near-death experience to make you re-evaluate your life so far. Luntz does just that on this week's Battleground. He tells Faiz and Amanda all the things he regrets, what he feels are his greatest mistakes and misses, and what he would do differently to save the Republican Party from itself.

node.title: GOP Pollster Frank Luntz Reveals His Biggest Regrets

node.text:
The entire downtown of Greenville, CA has been wiped out by the state’s raging Dixie Fire. Historical buildings, family homes, small businesses, elementary schools — all completely gone.

In a tearful address, Rep. Doug LaMalfa (R-CA), who represents Greenville, said: “There’s just not words for how us and government haven’t been able to get the job done for you. We’ll take up the fight even harder. We gotta get D.C. to pay attention.”

📸 AP/Noah Berger
